    "index_reference": "eliphaz",
    "language": "eng",
    "content": "<h1>ELIPHAZ</h1><p>1. Oldest son of Esau and his wife Adah (<a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen36:4-Gen36:16\">Gn 36:4–16</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Chr1:35-1Chr1:36\">1&nbsp;Chr 1:35–36</a>). He was the ancestor of a number of Edomite clans.</p><p>2. One of Job’s friends, called the Temanite (see <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer49:7\">Jer 49:7</a>). Teman was traditionally associated with wisdom; hence Eliphaz’s speech depicts the orthodox view of sin and punishment. His three addresses (<a href=\"https://ref.ly/Job4:1-Job4:21\">Jb 4</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Job15:1-Job15:35\">15</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Job22:1-Job22:30\">22</a>) failed to grapple with the essence of Job’s problem because he assumed previous major sin in Job’s life.</p><p><em>See also</em> <span data-bnType=\"resourceReference\" data-resourceId=\"5562\" data-resourceType=\"TyndaleBibleDictionary\">Job, Book of</span>.</p>",
